# Interrupt-Driven Event Controller

## Overview

This project implements an interrupt-driven push-button controller using an Arduino Uno. A hardware interrupt on digital pin 2 detects button presses, and each accepted event toggles an LED connected to digital pin 8.

The interrupt service routine is intentionally short. It only records that an interrupt occurred and returns immediately. Debouncing, LED control, event counting, status reporting, and Serial Monitor command processing are performed in the main program.

This design demonstrates practical interrupt handling, safe data sharing between an ISR and the main loop, software debouncing, and event-driven embedded control.

## Project Status

**Completed**

## Main Features

- External interrupt on Arduino Uno pin 2
- Push-button input using `INPUT_PULLUP`
- Falling-edge interrupt detection
- Minimal interrupt service routine
- Software button debouncing
- LED toggle after each accepted press
- Accepted-event counter
- Raw interrupt counter
- Rejected-bounce counter
- Interrupt enable and disable commands
- Adjustable debounce interval
- Manual LED commands
- Atomic access to shared multi-byte data
- Fixed-size serial command buffer
- Input validation
- Status and help commands

